		<h4><div>Winnipeg music icons<br>Earl Stafford and Eric Lussier</div></h4>
		<p>If you attended a Royal Winnipeg Ballet performance between 1984 and 2009, you&rsquo;ve heard Earl Stafford in action. Everyone knows this Winnipeg icon in that connection, but they may not be aware of Stafford&rsquo;s international career as an orchestral conductor. In fact, he has conducted the MCO before, stepping in to conduct <i>The Soldier&rsquo;s Tale</i> in 2013.</p>
		<p>Speaking of iconic Winnipeg musicians, we&rsquo;ve really got two guest conductors for this concert, as Eric Lussier will play / conduct JS Bach&rsquo;s A Major harpsichord concerto (BWV 1055). This wonderful piece likely premiered in 1739 at Zimmerman&rsquo;s coffee-house in Leipzig during Bach&rsquo;s tenure as director of the <i>Collegium musicum</i>.</p>
		<p><b>Eric Lussier &amp; the baroque</b></p>
		<p>Mention the word &lsquo;baroque&rsquo; in Winnipeg, and Eric Lussier&rsquo;s name comes to mind! He was the founding Artistic Director and Conductor of MusikBarock Ensemble which, under his leadership, grew to be a leading musical force in Winnipeg&rsquo;s cultural scene.</p>
		<p>The Manitoba Chamber Orchestra&rsquo;s own music library basically doubled in size when, in 2012, Lussier donated his considerable baroque orchestral collection to the MCO.</p>
		<p>Cheers, Eric!</p>

